#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:2
msgid "math - perform mathematics calculations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:5
msgid "Synopsis"
msgstr "概要"

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:7
msgid ""
"math [(-s | --scale) N] [(-b | --base) BASE] [(-m | --scale-mode) MODE] "
"EXPRESSION ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:13
msgid "Description"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:15
msgid ""
"``math`` performs mathematical calculations. It supports simple operations "
"such as addition, subtraction, and so on, as well as functions like "
"``abs()``, ``sqrt()`` and ``ln()``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:18
msgid ""
"By default, the output shows up to 6 decimal places. To change the number of "
"decimal places, use the ``--scale`` option, including ``--scale=0`` for "
"integer output."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:21
msgid ""
"Keep in mind that parameter expansion happens before expressions are "
"evaluated. This can be very useful in order to perform calculations "
"involving shell variables or the output of command substitutions, but it "
"also means that parenthesis (``()``) and the asterisk (``*``) glob character "
"have to be escaped or quoted. ``x`` can also be used to denote "
"multiplication, but it needs to be followed by whitespace to distinguish it "
"from hexadecimal numbers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:25
msgid ""
"Parentheses for functions are optional - ``math sin pi`` prints ``0``. "
"However, a comma will bind to the inner function, so ``math pow sin 3, 5`` "
"is an error because it tries to give ``sin`` the arguments ``3`` and ``5``. "
"When in doubt, use parentheses."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:29
msgid ""
"``math`` ignores whitespace between arguments and takes its input as "
"multiple arguments (internally joined with a space), so ``math 2 +2`` and "
"``math \"2 +    2\"`` work the same. ``math 2 2`` is an error."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:34
msgid ""
"math is a simple tool for simple uses, provided for convenience. It "
"internally works with floats for simplicity of implementation and can't do a "
"number of things real calculators can. If you find yourself limited by that, "
"use a more full-featured tool."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:37
msgid "The following options are available:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:39
msgid "**-s** *N* or **--scale** *N*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:40
msgid ""
"Sets the scale of the result. ``N`` must be an integer or the word \"max\" "
"for the maximum scale. A scale of zero causes results to be truncated by "
"default. Any non-integer component is thrown away. So ``3/2`` returns ``1`` "
"by default, rather than ``2`` which ``1.5`` would normally round to. This is "
"for compatibility with ``bc`` which was the basis for this command prior to "
"fish 3.0.0. Scale values greater than zero causes the result to be rounded "
"using the usual rules to the specified number of decimal places."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:47
msgid "**-b** *BASE* or **--base** *BASE*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:48
msgid ""
"Sets the numeric base used for output (``math`` always understands "
"hexadecimal numbers as input). It currently understands \"hex\" or \"16\" "
"for hexadecimal and \"octal\" or \"8\" for octal and implies a scale of 0 "
"(other scales cause an error), so it will truncate the result down to an "
"integer. This might change in the future. Hex numbers will be printed with a "
"``0x`` prefix. Octal numbers will have a prefix of ``0`` but aren't "
"understood by ``math`` as input."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:54
msgid "**-m** *MODE* or **--scale-mode** *MODE*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:55
msgid ""
"Sets scale behavior. The ``MODE`` can be ``truncate``, ``round``, ``floor``, "
"``ceiling``. The default value of scale mode is ``round`` with non zero "
"scale and ``truncate`` with zero scale."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:59
msgid "**-h** or **--help**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:60
msgid "Displays help about using this command."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:63
msgid "Return Values"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:65
msgid ""
"If the expression is successfully evaluated and doesn't over/underflow or "
"return NaN the return ``status`` is zero (success) else one."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:68
msgid "Syntax"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:70
msgid ""
"``math`` knows some operators, constants, functions and can (obviously) read "
"numbers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:72
msgid ""
"For numbers, ``.`` is always the radix character regardless of locale - "
"``2.5``, not ``2,5``. Scientific notation (``10e5``) and hexadecimal "
"(``0xFF``) are also available."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:75
msgid ""
"``math`` allows you to use underscores as visual separators for digit "
"grouping. For example, you can write ``1_000_000``, ``0x_89_AB_CD_EF``, and "
"``1.234_567_e89``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:78
msgid "Operators"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:80
msgid "``math`` knows the following operators:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:82
msgid "``+``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:83
msgid "for addition"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:84
msgid "``-``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:85
msgid "for subtraction"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:86
msgid "``*`` or ``x``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:87
msgid ""
"for multiplication. ``*`` is the glob character and needs to be quoted or "
"escaped, ``x`` needs to be followed by whitespace or it looks like ``0x`` "
"hexadecimal notation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:88
msgid "``/``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:89
msgid "for division"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:90
msgid "``^``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:91
msgid "for exponentiation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:92
msgid "``%``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:93
msgid "for modulo"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:94
msgid "``(`` or ``)``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:95
msgid ""
"for grouping. These need to be quoted or escaped because ``()`` denotes a "
"command substitution."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:97
msgid "They are all used in an infix manner - ``5 + 2``, not ``+ 5 2``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:100
msgid "Constants"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:102
msgid "``math`` knows the following constants:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:104
msgid "``e``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:105
msgid "Euler's number"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:106
msgid "``pi``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:107
msgid "π, you know this one. Half of Tau"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:109
msgid "``tau``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:110
msgid "Equivalent to 2π, or the number of radians in a circle"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:112
msgid "Use them without a leading ``$`` - ``pi - 3`` should be about 0."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:115
msgid "Functions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:117
msgid "``math`` supports the following functions:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:119
msgid "``abs``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:120
msgid "the absolute value, with positive sign"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:121
msgid "``acos``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:122
msgid "arc cosine"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:123
msgid "``asin``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:124
msgid "arc sine"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:125
msgid "``atan``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:126
msgid "arc tangent"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:127
msgid "``atan2``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:128
msgid "arc tangent of two variables"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:129
msgid "``bitand``, ``bitor`` and ``bitxor``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:130
msgid ""
"perform bitwise operations. These will throw away any non-integer parts and "
"interpret the rest as an int."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:133
msgid ""
"Note: ``bitnot`` and ``bitnand`` don't exist. This is because numbers in "
"math don't really have a *width* in terms of bits, and these operations "
"necessarily care about leading zeroes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:136
msgid ""
"If you need to negate a specific number you can do it with an xor with a "
"mask, e.g.::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:138
msgid ""
"> math --base=hex bitxor 0x0F, 0xFF\n"
"0xF0\n"
"\n"
"> math --base=hex bitxor 0x2, 0x3\n"
"# Here we mask with 0x3 == 0b111, so our number is 3 bits wide\n"
"# Only the 1 bit isn't set.\n"
"0x1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:146
msgid "``ceil``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:147
msgid "round number up to the nearest integer"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:148
msgid "``cos``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:149
msgid "the cosine"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:150
msgid "``cosh``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:151
msgid "hyperbolic cosine"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:152
msgid "``exp``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:153
msgid "the base-e exponential function"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:154
msgid "``fac``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:155
msgid "factorial - also known as ``x!`` (``x * (x - 1) * (x - 2) * ... * 1``)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:156
msgid "``floor``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:157
msgid "round number down to the nearest integer"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:158
msgid "``ln``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:159
msgid "the base-e logarithm"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:160
msgid "``log`` or ``log10``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:161
msgid ""
"the base-10 logarithm. To compute the logarithm for an arbitrary base ``b``, "
"use ``log(x) / log(b)``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:162
msgid "``log2``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:163
msgid "the base-2 logarithm"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:164
msgid "``max``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:165
msgid ""
"returns the largest of the given numbers - this takes an arbitrary number of "
"arguments (but at least one)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:166
msgid "``min``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:167
msgid ""
"returns the smallest of the given numbers - this takes an arbitrary number "
"of arguments (but at least one)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:168
msgid "``ncr``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:169
msgid ""
"\"from n choose r\" combination function - how many subsets of size r can be "
"taken from n (order doesn't matter)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:170
msgid "``npr``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:171
msgid ""
"the number of subsets of size r that can be taken from a set of n elements "
"(including different order)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:172
msgid "``pow(x,y)``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:173
msgid "returns x to the y (and can be written as ``x ^ y``)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:174
msgid "``round``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:175
msgid "rounds to the nearest integer, away from 0"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:176
msgid "``sin``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:177
msgid "the sine function"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:178
msgid "``sinh``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:179
msgid "the hyperbolic sine"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:180
msgid "``sqrt``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:181
msgid "the square root - (can also be written as ``x ^ 0.5``)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:182
msgid "``tan``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:183
msgid "the tangent"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:184
msgid "``tanh``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:185
msgid "the hyperbolic tangent"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:187
msgid ""
"All of the trigonometric functions use radians (the pi-based scale, not "
"360°)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:190
msgid "Examples"
msgstr "範例"

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:192
msgid "``math 1+1`` outputs 2."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:194
msgid ""
"``math $status - 128`` outputs the numerical exit status of the last command "
"minus 128."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:196
msgid "``math 10 / 6`` outputs ``1.666667``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:198
msgid "``math -s0 10.0 / 6.0`` outputs ``1``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:200
msgid "``math -s3 10 / 6`` outputs ``1.667``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:202
msgid "``math \"sin(pi)\"`` outputs ``0``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:204
msgid ""
"``math 5 \\* 2`` or ``math \"5 * 2\"`` or ``math 5 \"*\" 2`` all output "
"``10``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:206
msgid ""
"``math 0xFF`` outputs 255, ``math 0 x 3`` outputs 0 (because it computes 0 "
"multiplied by 3)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:208
msgid "``math bitand 0xFE, 0x2e`` outputs 46."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:210
msgid "``math \"bitor(9,2)\"`` outputs 11."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:212
msgid "``math --base=hex 192`` prints ``0xc0``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:214
msgid ""
"``math 'ncr(49,6)'`` prints 13983816 - that's the number of possible picks "
"in 6-from-49 lotto."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:216
msgid "``math max 5,2,3,1`` prints 5."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:219
msgid "Compatibility notes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:221
msgid ""
"Fish 1.x and 2.x releases relied on the ``bc`` command for handling ``math`` "
"expressions. Starting with fish 3.0.0 fish uses the tinyexpr library and "
"evaluates the expression without the involvement of any external commands."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/math.rst:223
msgid ""
"You don't need to use ``--`` before the expression, even if it begins with a "
"minus sign which might otherwise be interpreted as an invalid option. If you "
"do insert ``--`` before the expression, it will cause option scanning to "
"stop just like for every other command and it won't be part of the "
"expression."
msgstr ""
